<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-185-144 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 542 366</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  April 1 1991 v8 n13 p1(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>EDI: bottom-line booster or budget-breaker? (Electronic DataInterchange)(includes related articles on legal advice for EDIusers and internal use of EDI)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Salamone, Salvatore.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Network managers looking to implement electronic data interchange(EDI) should be aware of its potential benefits and challenges.andO;EDI can increase efficiency of interorganizational shipments aswell as decrease the number of times documents are processed byhuman operators.andP;  The standard, however, can be very expensive andsignificant savings on the cost of data entry staff has yet to beseen.andP;  The biggest cost that managers must factor into aconversion to EDI comes when integrating an application into anEDI system.andP;  Another expense is in installing controls over EDIapplications, such as checking authorization and messages forerrors.andP;  The network manager must also decide which EDI format touse.andP;  The dominant standard in North America is ANSI X12 butglobally the EDIFACT standard is gaining increasing support.andP;  Someanalysts contend that EDIFACT will eventually become the globalstandard.andP;  Further details are presented.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Electronic Data InterchangeNetwork ManagementCost of CommunicationsData EntryEDIFACT (Computer Network Protocol)System Conversion.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtablechart.andO;Caption:   1990 EDI net services market. (graph)The ABCs of EDI. (table)Integrating EDI over E-mail. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>